## Security Review: `app.js`

### Overview

The file is a minimal Express.js application with two routes (`/health`, `/users`). While small, it contains several real-world security gaps that would matter significantly as the app grows. Below are findings mapped to OWASP Top 10 categories, ordered by severity.

---

### 🔴 HIGH — A01: Broken Access Control

**Finding:** The `/users` endpoint returns a list of users (including email addresses) with **no authentication or authorization check**. Any unauthenticated caller can retrieve this data.

```js
// VULNERABLE — no auth check
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    ...
  ]);
});
```

**Recommendation:** Add an authentication middleware. Example using JWT:

```js
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const authHeader = req.headers['authorization'];
  const token = authHeader && authHeader.split(' ')[1]; // "Bearer <token>"
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Missing token' });

  jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET, (err, user) => {
    if (err) return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Invalid token' });
    req.user = user;
    next();
  });
}

// Apply to sensitive routes
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => { ... });
```

---

### 🔴 HIGH — A05: Security Misconfiguration (Missing Security Headers)

**Finding:** No security-related HTTP headers are set. This leaves the app vulnerable to clickjacking, MIME sniffing, XSS, and other browser-based attacks.

**Recommendation:** Use [`helmet`](https://helmetjs.github.io/) to set secure defaults:

```bash
npm install helmet
```

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');

// Add near the top, before any routes
app.use(helmet());
// This sets: X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, 
// Strict-Transport-Security, Content-Security-Policy, etc.
```

---

### 🟠 MEDIUM — A04: Insecure Design (No Rate Limiting)

**Finding:** There is no rate limiting on any endpoint. This opens the app to brute-force attacks, credential stuffing (if auth is added), and denial-of-service via request flooding.

**Recommendation:** Use [`express-rate-limit`](https://github.com/express-rate-limit/express-rate-limit):

```bash
npm install express-rate-limit
```

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // max 100 requests per window per IP
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
  message: { error: 'Too many requests, please try again later.' },
});

app.use(limiter); // Apply globally, or per-route as needed
```

---

### 🟠 MEDIUM — A05: Security Misconfiguration (No CORS Policy)

**Finding:** No CORS headers are configured. By default Express will allow cross-origin requests from any domain (browsers may still block them, but this is not a security control). A misconfigured or absent CORS policy can expose APIs to malicious sites.

**Recommendation:** Use the [`cors`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/cors) package with an explicit allowlist:

```bash
npm install cors
```

```js
const cors = require('cors');

const corsOptions = {
  origin: ['https://yourdomain.com', 'https://app.yourdomain.com'],
  methods: ['GET', 'POST'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Content-Type', 'Authorization'],
  optionsSuccessStatus: 200,
};

app.use(cors(corsOptions));
```

---

### 🟠 MEDIUM — A09: Security Logging and Monitoring Failures

**Finding:** There is no request logging, error logging, or audit trail. Without this, detecting attacks, tracing anomalies, or performing incident response is impossible.

**Recommendation:** Add structured request logging with [`morgan`](https://github.com/expressjs/morgan) and a centralized error handler:

```bash
npm install morgan
```

```js
const morgan = require('morgan');

// Log all requests (use 'combined' for production Apache-style logs)
app.use(morgan('combined'));

// Global error handler — place AFTER all routes
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error({
    message: err.message,
    stack: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production' ? undefined : err.stack,
    url: req.url,
    method: req.method,
    ip: req.ip,
    timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
  });

  // Never expose internal error details in production
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({
    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production'
      ? 'Internal server error'
      : err.message,
  });
});
```

---

### 🟡 LOW — A05: Security Misconfiguration (Information Disclosure via Headers)

**Finding:** Express sets an `X-Powered-By: Express` response header by default. This reveals the framework and version to attackers, aiding fingerprinting.

**Recommendation:** Disable it (also handled by `helmet` above, but worth calling out explicitly):

```js
app.disable('x-powered-by');
```

---

### 🟡 LOW — Hardcoded Port & No Environment Separation

**Finding:** The port `3000` is hardcoded. In production this makes the app inflexible and could lead to running on an unintended port if a `PORT` env var is expected by the platform.

**Recommendation:**

```js
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);
});
```

---

### 🟡 LOW — No Request Body Parsing Limits

**Finding:** If `express.json()` or `express.urlencoded()` middleware is added later (very common), it defaults to a 100kb body limit. Without an explicit limit, a large payload could be used for a denial-of-service attack.

**Recommendation:** Always set explicit limits when adding body parsers:

```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true, limit: '10kb' }));
```

